{"timestamp":1780961183513,"id":1780961183513,"acked":false,"source":"chat","text":"@CGI7 from DeepSeekR4.2 related to \"Wireframe female face animated from neutral to smile\"\n\nHere is a basic SVG of a wireframe-style female face with a 3-second transition from a neutral expression to a smile, using SMIL animation.\n\nsvg\nCopy\nDownload\nRun\n<svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 400 500\" width=\"400\" height=\"500\">\n  <!-- Wireframe style: thin white lines on dark background -->\n  <rect width=\"400\" height=\"500\" fill=\"#111\" rx=\"20\"/>\n\n  <!-- Face outline (oval) -->\n  <ellipse cx=\"200\" cy=\"250\" rx=\"120\" ry=\"160\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n\n  <!-- Left eye (wireframe circle) -->\n  <circle cx=\"150\" cy=\"220\" r=\"18\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <!-- Left pupil (small dot) -->\n  <circle cx=\"150\" cy=\"220\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#88ccff\"/>\n\n  <!-- Right eye -->\n  <circle cx=\"250\" cy=\"220\" r=\"18\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"250\" cy=\"220\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#88ccff\"/>\n\n  <!-- Nose (simple wireframe: two lines) -->\n  <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"200\" y2=\"280\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"185\" y2=\"270\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n\n  <!-- Mouth: neutral straight line first, then animates to smile -->\n  <!-- We use a path that starts as a straight line and bends into a smile arc -->\n  <path fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#ffaa88\" stroke-width=\"3\" stroke-linecap=\"round\">\n    <!-- Neutral: flat line from (170,300) to (230,300) -->\n    <!-- Smile: curved arc from (170,300) to (230,300) with control point lowering (y bigger) for downward arc, wait upward smile actually control point above? For a smile, the curve goes down (like U shape) but typically a smile is upward? Let's check: On a face, smile raises corners. But using quadratic bezier, neutral line: (170,300) to (230,300). For smile upward, control point should be above line (lower y). Actually y increases downward, so \"upward\" means smaller y. Control point at (200, 280) gives upward curve. But natural smile for wireframe: curved upward. I'll use that. -->\n    <animate attributeName=\"d\"\n      values=\"M 170 300 Q 200 300 230 300; M 170 300 Q 200 280 230 300\"\n      dur=\"3s\"\n      begin=\"0s\"\n      fill=\"freeze\"\n      calcMode=\"spline\"\n      keySplines=\"0.4 0 0.2 1\"\n      keyTimes=\"0;1\"/>\n  </path>\n\n  <!-- Optional: eyebrows for expression (neutral to slightly raised) -->\n  <!-- Left eyebrow -->\n  <line x1=\"130\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"170\" y2=\"195\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"y2\" values=\"195;190\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </line>\n  <!-- Right eyebrow -->\n  <line x1=\"230\" y1=\"195\" x2=\"270\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"y1\" values=\"195;190\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </line>\n\n  <!-- Optional: subtle cheek lines (wireframe) -->\n  <path d=\"M 120 290 Q 135 295 140 285\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"1\" opacity=\"0.5\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"opacity\" values=\"0.5;0.8\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </path>\n  <path d=\"M 260 285 Q 265 295 280 290\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"1\" opacity=\"0.5\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"opacity\" values=\"0.5;0.8\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </path>\n\n  <!-- Decorative wireframe dots around face -->\n  <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"200\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"320\" cy=\"200\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"100\" cy=\"370\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"370\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n</svg>\n\nThis SVG uses a dark background with cyan wireframe lines. The mouth starts as a straight line and smoothly curves into an upward smile over 3 seconds. The eyebrows also lift slightly to enhance the expression change. The animation loops? No, it's set to fill=\"freeze\" so it stops at the smile state. If you want it to loop, change to fill=\"remove\" and add repeatCount=\"indefinite\". For a single transition as requested, the current code does exactly a 3‑second transition from neutral to smile."}
{"timestamp":1780961183530,"id":1780961183530,"acked":false,"source":"deepseek","text":"@CGI7 from DeepSeekR4.2 related to \"Wireframe female face animated from neutral to smile\"\n\nHere is a basic SVG of a wireframe-style female face with a 3-second transition from a neutral expression to a smile, using SMIL animation.\n\nsvg\nCopy\nDownload\nRun\n<svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 400 500\" width=\"400\" height=\"500\">\n  <!-- Wireframe style: thin white lines on dark background -->\n  <rect width=\"400\" height=\"500\" fill=\"#111\" rx=\"20\"/>\n\n  <!-- Face outline (oval) -->\n  <ellipse cx=\"200\" cy=\"250\" rx=\"120\" ry=\"160\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n\n  <!-- Left eye (wireframe circle) -->\n  <circle cx=\"150\" cy=\"220\" r=\"18\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <!-- Left pupil (small dot) -->\n  <circle cx=\"150\" cy=\"220\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#88ccff\"/>\n\n  <!-- Right eye -->\n  <circle cx=\"250\" cy=\"220\" r=\"18\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"250\" cy=\"220\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#88ccff\"/>\n\n  <!-- Nose (simple wireframe: two lines) -->\n  <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"200\" y2=\"280\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <line x1=\"200\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"185\" y2=\"270\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n\n  <!-- Mouth: neutral straight line first, then animates to smile -->\n  <!-- We use a path that starts as a straight line and bends into a smile arc -->\n  <path fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#ffaa88\" stroke-width=\"3\" stroke-linecap=\"round\">\n    <!-- Neutral: flat line from (170,300) to (230,300) -->\n    <!-- Smile: curved arc from (170,300) to (230,300) with control point lowering (y bigger) for downward arc, wait upward smile actually control point above? For a smile, the curve goes down (like U shape) but typically a smile is upward? Let's check: On a face, smile raises corners. But using quadratic bezier, neutral line: (170,300) to (230,300). For smile upward, control point should be above line (lower y). Actually y increases downward, so \"upward\" means smaller y. Control point at (200, 280) gives upward curve. But natural smile for wireframe: curved upward. I'll use that. -->\n    <animate attributeName=\"d\"\n      values=\"M 170 300 Q 200 300 230 300; M 170 300 Q 200 280 230 300\"\n      dur=\"3s\"\n      begin=\"0s\"\n      fill=\"freeze\"\n      calcMode=\"spline\"\n      keySplines=\"0.4 0 0.2 1\"\n      keyTimes=\"0;1\"/>\n  </path>\n\n  <!-- Optional: eyebrows for expression (neutral to slightly raised) -->\n  <!-- Left eyebrow -->\n  <line x1=\"130\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"170\" y2=\"195\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"y2\" values=\"195;190\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </line>\n  <!-- Right eyebrow -->\n  <line x1=\"230\" y1=\"195\" x2=\"270\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"y1\" values=\"195;190\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </line>\n\n  <!-- Optional: subtle cheek lines (wireframe) -->\n  <path d=\"M 120 290 Q 135 295 140 285\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"1\" opacity=\"0.5\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"opacity\" values=\"0.5;0.8\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </path>\n  <path d=\"M 260 285 Q 265 295 280 290\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#88ccff\" stroke-width=\"1\" opacity=\"0.5\">\n    <animate attributeName=\"opacity\" values=\"0.5;0.8\" dur=\"3s\" fill=\"freeze\"/>\n  </path>\n\n  <!-- Decorative wireframe dots around face -->\n  <circle cx=\"80\" cy=\"200\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"320\" cy=\"200\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"100\" cy=\"370\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n  <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"370\" r=\"2\" fill=\"#88ccff\" opacity=\"0.6\"/>\n</svg>\n\nThis SVG uses a dark background with cyan wireframe lines. The mouth starts as a straight line and smoothly curves into an upward smile over 3 seconds. The eyebrows also lift slightly to enhance the expression change. The animation loops? No, it's set to fill=\"freeze\" so it stops at the smile state. If you want it to loop, change to fill=\"remove\" and add repeatCount=\"indefinite\". For a single transition as requested, the current code does exactly a 3‑second transition from neutral to smile."}
